  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is an air conveyor for beverage bottles?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>An air conveyor suspends empty PET bottles from their neck rings and propels them with pressurized air jets at speeds up to 2000+ bottles per minute. No belt contact with the bottle body — eliminates scuffing and contamination. Connects blow molders to fillers on high-speed beverage lines.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What conveyor speeds do beverage lines run?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>High-speed PET water and CSD lines run 600-2000+ CPM. Beer lines run 100-2000+ CPM depending on operation scale. Juice and dairy run 100-400 CPM. Spirits and wine run 50-200 CPM. The filler sets line speed; conveyors run faster to provide accumulation buffer.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a mass flow accumulator?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A wide conveyor section where containers spread from single file into multiple rows side-by-side, providing buffer capacity between machines. When a downstream machine stops, containers accumulate on the wide table. When it restarts, containers funnel back into single file. <a href="/conveyor-functions/storage-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Serpentine accumulators</a> offer similar buffering in a smaller footprint.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Why do beverage conveyors need wet environment design?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Beverage plants use water for rinsing, pasteurizing, cooling, CIP cleaning, and daily washdown. Conveyors operate in standing water and spray zones. All components need corrosion resistance (304/316 stainless steel frames, plastic chains), sealed bearings (IP67/IP69K), and drainage designs that prevent bacterial harborage.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
